surveys.narrative: Mills Lake is located southeast of Lake Crystal and west of highway 169. This fairly small (230 acre) lake has a maximum depth of about 7 feet. A fishery survey was conducted on Mills Lake in August 2004 to assess the fish community and aquatic habitat. Mills Lake was reclaimed in 1998, however common carp and black bullhead became reestablished soon after the reclamation due to failure of the outlet barrier. By 2000, black bullhead dominated the fish community. Low oxygen conditions occurred in the winter of 2000 to 2001 resulting in some winterkill of fish. Black bullhead had further increased in abundance in 2003 and 2004. In 2004, black bullhead were mostly 5 to 6 inches in length. Some northern pike are present and are generally large, from 20 to 30 inches in length. Bluegill and black crappie were present in moderate numbers. Black crappie were mostly around 7 to 8 inches and the bluegill were around 6 to 7 inches long. A public access is located off of highway 169. An aeration system is operated on this lake in the winter. Use caution when traveling on the ice.

Mills Lake is located southeast of Lake Crystal and off highway 169. This small (230 acre) lake has a maximum depth of 7 feet. Mills Lake has a good population of 7 - 8.5 inch black crappie and low abundance of northern pike, yellow perch, bluegill and largemouth bass. There is a good population of 8.5 - 10 inch black bullhead that average a half pound.

A fishery population assessment was conducted on Mills Lake in August 2003 to assess the fish community following reclamation and winterkill. Mills Lake was reclaimed in 1998, however common carp and black bullhead became reestablished soon after the reclamation due to failure of the outlet barrier. By 2000, black bullhead dominated the fish community. Low oxygen conditions occurred in the winter of 2000 to 2001 resulting in some winterkill of fish. Black bullhead had further increased in abundance in 2003. Northern pike are present at a moderate abundance. Most were between 20 and 30 inches in length. Some black crappie, bluegill, largemouth bass, and yellow perch are present. Some black crappie were up to 11 inches long and the largest bluegills were 8 inches.

MILLS LAKE LAST EXPERIENCED A WINTERKILL IN 1986, AND WALLEYE FRY WERE STOCKED AT THAT TIME, OTHER SPECIES PRESENT APPARENTLY MIGRATED IN FROM LOON LAKE DURING SPRING RUN-OFF. BLUEGILLS WERE SAMPLED IN RELATIVELY HIGH NUMBERS AVERAGING 61.33/TRAP NET. ALL BLUEGILLS SAMPLED WERE 2 YEAR OLDS AND SHOW FAST GROWTH. MOST OF THE BLUEGILLS NETTED RANGED FROM 4.5-5.4' INCHES LENGTH. PUMPKINSEED AVERAGED 5.00/TRAP NET AND WERE REPRESENTED BY 2, 3, AND 4 YEAR OLD FISH. MOST OF THE PUMPKINSEEDS SAMPLED WERE 4.0 - 5.4 INCHES IN LENGTH. YELLOW PERCH AVERAGED 14.00/GILL NET WITH AGES 1,2 AND 3 SAMPLED, WITH AGE 3 MOST NUMEROUS. PERCH WERE EVENLY DISTRIBUTED FROM 5.0 - 11.4 INCHES IN LENGTH. WALLEYES AVERAGED 5.00/GILL NET AND RANGED FROM 12.0-14.9 INCHES IN LENGTH. WALLEYES ARE 2 YEAR OLDS AND CORRESPOND TO THE 1986 FRY STOCKING. GROWTH IS FAST FOR WALLEYES WITH MOST FISH WEIGH- ING 3/4 - 1 LB. NORTHERN PIKE AVERAGED 7.50/GILL NET AND ALL THE FISH SAMPLED WERE 2 YR. OLDS. NORTHERNS WERE EVENLY DISTRIBUTED FROM 18.0-25.9 INCHES IN LENGTH, AND THEY SHOW FAST GROWTH RATES. BLACK BULLHEADS ARE ABUNDANT, AVERAGING 322.33/ TRAP NET AND 66.00/GILL NET WITH FISH 5.0-13.9 INCHES IN LENGTH. OTHER SPECIES PRESENT IN RELATIVELY LOW ABUNDANCE INCLUDE CARP, GOLDEN SHINER, YELLOW BULLHEAD, GREEN SUNFISH, AND GREEN X PUMPKINSEED HYBRIDS.

MILLS LAKE HAS A MARGINAL GAMEFISH POPULATION AND HAS EXPERIENCED FREQUENT WINTER KILLS. MILLS HAS BEEN USED AS A WAE REARING POND OVER THE YEARS AND AT TIMES PROVIDED A MILLS IS CURRENTLY BEING CONSIDERED FOR A CHEMICAL RECLAMATION IN 1992. BLB WERE ABUNDANT AVERAGING 390.25/TRAP NET AND APPEAR TO BE DOMINATED BY A SINGLE COHORT OF 6.0-7.4 INCH FISH. CARP AVERAGED 6.00/TRAP NET WITH MOST FISH 13.0-15.9 INCHES. OTHER SPECIES SAMPLED IN LOW ABUNDANCE INCLUDE BLG, PMK, HSF, AND YEB. IT IS SUSPECTED THAT MOST OF THE SPECIES PRESENT RECOLONIZED FROM LOON LAKE.
